sformation and sketches out a framework for more sustainable capitalism. State-mandated changes in energy use (as opposed to carbon taxes), a circular flow of resources (as opposed to emissions standards), and the introduction of new financial instruments that support green growth are cornerstones of China's framework. John A. Mathews argues that these tenets will be emulated around the world-first in India and Brazil. In light of this emerging shift, Mathews considers core debates over national security, international relations, and economic policy, ultimately addressing the question of whether these measures will be far-reaching or timely enough to prevent further damage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCapitalismxEnvironmental aspectsxAsia. 0aCapitalismxEnvironmental aspectszAsia. 0aEconomic developmentxEnvironmental aspectsxAsia. 0aEconomic developmentxEnvironmental aspectszAsia. 0aSustainable developmentxAsia. 0aSustainable developmentzAsia. 4aChina's green and black revolution. 4aclimate bonds. 4aclimate change. 4aeco-finance. 4aenergy security. 4afree-market environmentalism. 4aglobal warming. 4arenewable energies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804793162zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804793162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804793162.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles